Now I understand the issue. The problem is in the PCAP_WritePDU function at line 143 in `/repo/openair2/UTIL/OPT/probe.c`. The function calls `fflush(file_fd)` at line 196, which is causing a scheduling priority inversion.

The issue is that `fflush()` is a blocking I/O operation that can take significant time to complete. When this function is called from a high-priority context (like real-time scheduling threads in the MAC/PHY layers), the blocking I/O operation causes the high-priority thread to wait for disk I/O, effectively lowering its priority during the flush operation. Meanwhile, lower-priority threads can continue running.

This is a classic priority inversion problem where a high-priority thread is blocked waiting for a low-priority resource (disk I/O), allowing lower-priority threads to run ahead of it.

The fix is to remove the `fflush(file_fd)` call from the PCAP_WritePDU function. File I/O buffering will still work correctly - the data will be written to disk when the buffer fills up or when the file is closed. For a real-time system like this, it's better to let the OS manage the buffering rather than forcing a synchronous flush on every PDU write.

